---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const socialMediaLinks = [
  {
    name: "X",
    url: "",
    icon: "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/95/Twitter_new_X_logo.png",
  },
  {
    name: "Discord",
    url: "",
    icon: "https://cdn-icons-png.flaticon.com/512/4945/4945973.png",
  },
];
---

<Layout title="Welcome to Astro.">
  <main class="main sub-grid">
    <div>
      <h1 class="main-heading title">HTML Semantics and CSS Grid</h1>
      <p>Inspiration session #1</p>
    </div>
    <aside>
      <figure>
        <img
          src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/2380794/pexels-photo-2380794.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=600"
          alt="John Doe"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <p>Presenter: Proff John Doe</p>
          <p>
            John Doe is a web developer with over 10 years of experience. He has
            worked with realy really realy! big companies so he knows what he is
            talking about and its save to believe him.
          </p>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <address>
        <ul role="list" class="social-media-links">
          {
            socialMediaLinks.map((item) => {
              return (
                <li>
                  <a href="#" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                    <span class="icon">
                      <img src={item.icon} alt="Twitter" />
                    </span>
                  </a>
                </li>
              );
            })
          }
        </ul>
      </address>
    </aside>
    <article>
      <h2>The Art of Architecture and HTML Semantics</h2>
      <p>
        Just as the grand architects of history have laid down stone upon stone
        to build the wonders of the world, so do web developers lay down tags
        upon tags to construct the digital realms we navigate daily. But beware,
        for not all tags are created equal, and herein lies the art of HTML
        semantics.
      </p>
      <p>
        Imagine, if you will, a world where the Pyramids of Giza were built with
        playing cards instead of stone blocks. Sure, from a distance, it might
        still look impressive, but a single gust of wind (or a user with a
        screen reader) would reveal the shaky foundation beneath. This is the
        world without HTML semanticsâ€”a visually appealing facade, perhaps, but
        lacking in structure and accessibility.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <code>&lt;header&gt;</code> tag, much like the grand entrance to a stately
        manor, welcomes visitors and introduces them to the wonders within. The <code
          >&lt;nav&gt;</code
        > tag serves as the corridors, guiding visitors through the rooms of our
        digital edifice. The <code>&lt;main&gt;</code> and
        <code>&lt;article&gt;</code> tags are the chambers themselves, each filled
        with treasures of information. And let us not forget the <code
          >&lt;footer&gt;</code
        >, akin to the foundations of our buildings, grounding the site and
        providing essential information at the journey's end.
      </p>
      <p>
        But what of the ornate decorations that adorn our structures, the
        images, and videos that bring life to our pages? Here, too, semantics
        play a crucial role. The <code>&lt;figure&gt;</code> tag, with its faithful
        companion
        <code>&lt;figcaption&gt;</code>, ensures that our visual aids are not
        merely seen but understood, providing context and meaning.
      </p>
      <p>
        In conclusion, the art of architecture and HTML semantics share a common
        goal: to build structures that are not only beautiful but functional and
        accessible to all. As architects of the digital age, let us wield our
        tags with wisdom, crafting web pages that stand the test of time, just
        as the great monuments of old have done.
      </p>
    </article>
    <section>
      <h2>Upcoming Events</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Advanced CSS Techniques</strong> - April 15, 2023</li>
        <li><strong>JavaScript for Beginners</strong> - May 20, 2023</li>
        <li><strong>Building Responsive Layouts</strong> - June 10, 2023</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="cta">
      <h2>Stay Updated</h2>
      <p>
        Subscribe to our newsletter to get the latest updates on our workshops
        and events.
      </p>
      <form action="/subscribe" method="POST">
        <input
          type="email"
          name="email"
          placeholder="Enter your email"
          required
        />
        <button type="submit">Subscribe</button>
      </form>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>

<style>
  .main {
    display: grid;
    gap: 2.4rem;
    grid-column: 1 / -1;
    grid-row: 2;

    & > * {
      grid-column: 2 / -2;
    }

    h1 {
      font-size: 3.5rem;
      /* color: var(--_color-primary); */
    }

    & .main-heading.title + p {
      margin: 0;
    }

    ul {
      list-style: none;
      padding: 0;
      margin: 0;
    }

    aside {
      figure {
        margin-left: 0;
        margin-right: 0;
        max-width: 300px;
        img {
          border-radius: 50%;
          width: 100%;
          height: auto;
          translate: -20px 0;
        }
        figcaption {
          margin: 0;
        }
      }

      address {
        ul {
          display: flex;
          gap: 1rem;
          margin: 0;

          .icon {
            display: inline-block;
            width: 2.4rem;
            height: 2.4rem;
            border-radius: 50%;
            padding: 0.5rem;
            background-color: #000;
            overflow: hidden;
          }
        }
      }
    }

    article {
      h2 {
        font-size: 2.5rem;
        color: var(--_color-primary);
      }
    }

    section {
      margin-bottom: 2rem;
      ul {
        list-style: none;
        padding: 0;
        margin: 0;
        li {
          margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
        }
      }
    }
  }
</style>
